Looking at `_SelectableTextSelectionGestureDetectorBuilder` in `selectable_text.dart`, the class overrides `onSingleTapUp` but has no override for `onSecondaryTap`. So when you right-click, the base class implementation in `TextSelectionGestureDetectorBuilder.onSecondaryTap` (in `text_selection.dart`) runs directly. On macOS and web that method calls `renderEditable.selectWord(cause: SelectionChangedCause.tap)` whenever there is no existing selection at the tap point, which is exactly the unwanted behavior.

The fix is to add an `onSecondaryTap` override in `_SelectableTextSelectionGestureDetectorBuilder` that skips the word selection. Since `SelectableText` is always read-only, right-clicking should never expand the selection to a word:

```dart
@override
void onSecondaryTap() {
  if (!delegate.selectionEnabled) {
    return;
  }
  // SelectableText is read-only, so right-clicking should not select a word.
  // Only show the toolbar if text is already selected.
  if (shouldShowSelectionToolbar) {
    editableText.showToolbar();
  }
}
```

There is also a secondary contributor on web. `EditableText._shouldCreateInputConnection` in `editable_text.dart` returns `true` on web regardless of `readOnly`, which keeps an active text input connection open. The web engine then responds to the right-click by sending `TextInput.updateEditingValue` with a word selection range, and the framework applies that selection even though the widget is read-only. The override above stops the framework-side gesture from selecting a word, but a full web fix would also need `_shouldCreateInputConnection` to return `false` when `readOnly` is true and the connection is only needed for selection/clipboard purposes, not for text input.

Thanks for the kind words and for agreeing with the analysis, @Renzo-Olivares! 🙌

Looking at `onSecondaryTap` in `text_selection.dart`, the `selectWord` call is gated on `defaultTargetPlatform == TargetPlatform.macOS` with no `kIsWeb` check, so both macOS web and macOS desktop actually hit that path through the base class.

The base class behavior makes sense for `TextField` since it is editable. The argument for overriding it in `SelectableText` is that even on macOS native, right-clicking a non-editable text field (`NSTextField` with `isEditable = false`) just shows the context menu without selecting the word. `SelectableText` maps more closely to that than to an editable field. 🙂

That said, happy to go either way on the PR depending on what the team prefers:

**Option A** : keep the current override as-is (no word selection on any platform for `SelectableText`), and expand the test coverage to include Windows and Linux variants as well.

**Option B** : if word-selection-on-right-click should be preserved on macOS to match the platform convention, the override can fall through to `super.onSecondaryTap()` for `TargetPlatform.macOS`:

```dart
@override
void onSecondaryTap() {
  if (!delegate.selectionEnabled) return;
  if (defaultTargetPlatform == TargetPlatform.macOS) {
    super.onSecondaryTap();
    return;
  }
  final TextSelection selection = editableText.textEditingValue.selection;
  if (selection.isValid && !selection.isCollapsed) {
    editableText.showToolbar();
  }
}
```

Just let me know which direction to go and I'll update the PR! 👍

